</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[828,1437,689,2056]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis box="[858,914,785,808]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[932,1091,785,808]" captionStart="Figs 333–338" captionStartId="75.[151,188,1908,1927]" captionTargetBox="[159,1436,189,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-54@75.[151,1436,189,1897]" captionTargetPageId="75" captionText="Figs 333–338. Liroetis apicicornis Jacoby, 1896. 333–335 – Male, syntype (9.7 mm). 333 – dorsal view; 334 – ventral view; 335 – labels. 336–337 – Male (9.5 mm): 336 – dorsal view; 337 – head and pronotum. 338 – Female (10.3 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5821500" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5821500/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Figs 336–337</figureCitation>
). Antennae 0.62 times as long as body. Pronotum 1.95 times as wide as long, lustrous, almost impunctate, anterior margin bordered. Abdominal ventrite IV with small subtriangular process in middle of posterior margin, surrounding surface slightly impressed. Last abdominal ventrite with longitudinal impression narrower in posterior part, wider basally. Protarsomere I narrow, metatibial spur short, very thin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[828,1437,689,2056]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis box="[858,963,1041,1064]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Aedeagus</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[982,1081,1041,1064]" captionStart="Figs 347–351" captionStartId="78.[151,188,1354,1373]" captionTargetBox="[179,1399,212,1327]" captionTargetId="figure-13@78.[151,1436,189,1350]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="Figs 347–351. Aedeagus of Liroetis, dorsal and lateral views, apex of dorsal process in frontal view. 347 – L. apicicornis Jacoby, 1896; 348 – L. latispinus (Chen, 1976); 349 – L. pallidulus (Jiang, 1990); 350 – L. reitteri (Pic, 1934); 351 – L. violaceipennis Zhang, Li &amp; Yang, 2008. Fig. 348 reproduced from JංൺඇǤ (1990). Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5821506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5821506/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Fig. 347</figureCitation>
). Median lobe of aedeagus flat, lanceolate, 2.47 times as long as wide, widest in middle part; apical part subtriangular with incised tip. Lateral view: slightly bent, lateral elevation absent. Dorsal process short, 1.66 times as long as wide, 0.36 times as long as median lobe; apical part wide, covered with very long setae, in middle with wing-like structure; in lateral view Y-shaped.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[828,1437,689,2056]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis box="[858,937,1265,1288]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Female</emphasis>
. Metatibial spur absent. Last abdominal ventrite with posterior margin entire. Sternite VIII transversely suboval with triangular median process, posterior half of sternite VIII and median process covered with very long setae; tignum as long as sternite VIII, with asymmetrical oblique apex (
<figureCitation box="[972,1062,1425,1448]" captionStart="Figs 352–358" captionStartId="79.[151,188,1246,1265]" captionTargetBox="[157,1424,200,1227]" captionTargetId="figure-11@79.[151,1436,189,1243]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Figs 352–358. Spermatheca (Figs 352–354) and sternite VII (Figs 355–358) of Liroetis. 352, 355 – L. apicicornis Jacoby, 1896; 353, 356 – L. pallidulus (Jiang, 1990); 354, 358 – L. violaceipennis Zhang, Li &amp; Yang, 2008; 357 – L. reitteri (Pic, 1934). Scales 0.25 mm for Figs 352–354, 0.5 mm for Figs 355–358." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5821508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5821508/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Fig. 355</figureCitation>
). Spermatheca with suboval nodulus covered with traces of transverse wrinkles, cornu short C-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[943,1037,1489,1512]" captionStart="Figs 352–358" captionStartId="79.[151,188,1246,1265]" captionTargetBox="[157,1424,200,1227]" captionTargetId="figure-11@79.[151,1436,189,1243]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Figs 352–358. Spermatheca (Figs 352–354) and sternite VII (Figs 355–358) of Liroetis. 352, 355 – L. apicicornis Jacoby, 1896; 353, 356 – L. pallidulus (Jiang, 1990); 354, 358 – L. violaceipennis Zhang, Li &amp; Yang, 2008; 357 – L. reitteri (Pic, 1934). Scales 0.25 mm for Figs 352–354, 0.5 mm for Figs 355–358." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5821508" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5821508/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Fig. 352</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[828,1437,689,2056]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[828,1076,1521,1544]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1896" box="[1082,1291,1521,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicicornis">
<emphasis box="[1082,1291,1521,1544]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Liroetis apicicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by body, legs and antennae completely orange brown, with exception of two apical antennomeres that are black, median lobe of aedeagus flat and wide, with dorsal process short, and by pronotum nearly twice as wide as long. It is the only known species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Weise" authorityYear="1889" box="[1100,1181,1681,1704]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1100,1181,1681,1704]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Liroetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabiting south-eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[828,883,1713,1736]" name="India" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">India</collectingCountry>
and its distribution is disjunct from other species of the genus (the nearest species occur in Himalayas and easternmost 
<collectingCountry box="[965,1024,1777,1800]" name="India" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">India</collectingCountry>
). 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2021" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2021" box="[1044,1263,1777,1800]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurantiacus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1044,1263,1777,1800]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Liroetis aurantiacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1273,1358,1777,1800]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2021" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2021" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="603" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="baolocanus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">L. baolocanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[960,1045,1809,1832]" pageId="74" pageNumber="603" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from SE Asia have similarly transverse pronotum and similar colouration but they differ in completely brown antennae and very different structure of aedeagus (cf. 
<figureCitation box="[975,1097,1905,1928]" captionStart="Figs 65–71" captionStartId="20.[151,188,1622,1641]" captionTargetBox="[161,1414,192,1585]" captionTargetId="figure-13@20.[151,1436,176,1975]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs 65–71. Details of new species of Liroetis. 65–70 – L. aurantiacus sp. nov. 65 – Aedegus in dorsal, lateral and ventral views; 66 – female pygidium; 67 – spermatheca; 68 – sternite VIII; 69 – male abdomen in ventral and lateral views. 70–71 – L. baolocanus sp. nov. 70 – Aedegus in dorsal, lateral and ventral views; 71 – male abdomen in ventral and lateral views. Scales: 0.5 mm for Figs 65–66, 68 and 70, 0.25 mm for Fig. 67; 1 mm for Figs 69, 71." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5821391" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5821391/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">Figs 65, 70</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1108,1152,1905,1928]" captionStart="Figs 347–351" captionStartId="78.[151,188,1354,1373]" captionTargetBox="[179,1399,212,1327]" captionTargetId="figure-13@78.[151,1436,189,1350]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="Figs 347–351. Aedeagus of Liroetis, dorsal and lateral views, apex of dorsal process in frontal view. 347 – L. apicicornis Jacoby, 1896; 348 – L. latispinus (Chen, 1976); 349 – L. pallidulus (Jiang, 1990); 350 – L. reitteri (Pic, 1934); 351 – L. violaceipennis Zhang, Li &amp; Yang, 2008. Fig. 348 reproduced from JංൺඇǤ (1990). Scale 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5821506" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5821506/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="603">347</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
